#Text=Jan Suchorzewski
#Text=Portrait of Suchorzewski
#Text=Jan Suchorzewski ( 1740 or 1754 – 1804 or 1809 ) [ a ] was a Polish noble of the Zaremba coat of arms , soldier and politician .
#Text=He held the title of the wojski of Wschowa . [ 1 ]
#Text=He was a deputy from Gniezno to the Sejm ( parliament ) of 1786 and deputy from Kalisz to the Great Sejm of 1788-1792. [ 1 ]
#Text=He would be best remembered for his dramatic , theatrical gestures from that period .
#Text=Kazimierz Bartoszewicz compared Suchorzewski 's look and attitude to that of Zagłoba from Henryk Sienkiewicz 's famous trilogy , if more misguided . [ 2 ]
#Text=He became an opponent of the reforms , and joined the Confederation of Targowica . [ 1 ]
#Text=Biography
#Text=Jan was born in 1740 or 1754 as the son of Jakub Suchorzewski and Jadwiga Zajączek . [ 3 ]
#Text=Around 1770 he married Joanna Przyjemska ; they had three children . [ 3 ]
#Text=During the Great Sejm Suchorzewski was at first a supporter of the Patriotic Party ; in particular he supported the enlargement of the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth 's army . [ 4 ] [ 5 ] [ 6 ]
#Text=In 1789 he published a brochure on the cities and law ( Basics of urban laws - Zasady praw miejskich ) . [ 7 ]
#Text=However , he eventually switched sides and joined the Hetman Party opposed to the reforms . [ 1 ] [ 4 ]

#Text=Around 18 January 1791 he criticized the recently premiered The Return of the Deputy ( Powrót posła ) comedy of Julian Ursyn Niemcewicz for its political content ; his critique was not well received and he was ridiculed for it , losing prestige . [ 8 ] [ 9 ] [ 10 ]

#Text=Despite his opposition of many reforms , he nonetheless played a major , if perhaps not necessarily intentional , [ 11 ] role in the passage of the Free Royal Cities Act in April 1791 , as his rather unexpected involvement in the discussion boosted the supporters of the act and eased its passing . [ 12 ] [ 13 ]
#Text=For that , the king rewarded him with the Order of Saint Stanislaus . [ 10 ]

#Text=Suchorzewski unsuccessfully attempted to prevent the king from signing the Constitution of 3 May , blocking his way and threatening to kill his own son to save him from the " slavery of the Constitution " . [ 14 ] [ 15 ] [ 16 ] [ b ]
#Text=In this way he repeated , in an infamous , or tragicomic way , the gesture of Tadeusz Rejtan . [ 17 ] [ 18 ]
#Text=This incident was immortalized on Jan Matejko 's painting Constitution of May 3 , 1791 . [ 14 ] [ 15 ]

#Text=From Suchorzewski 's pocket , a deck of cards has fallen out , an allusion to the way he was bribed by the Hetman Party leaders , Russian ambassador Otto Magnus von Stackelberg and hetman Branicki . [ 14 ] [ 14 ] [ 15 ]

#Text=Later , he would publish a critique of the constitution in the brochure Uwagi nad konstytucją polską 3 maja 1791 ( Notes on the Polish Constitution of 3 May 1791 ) [ 7 ] and Odezwa do narodu wraz z protestacyją dla Śladu Gwałtu i Przemocy , do której prawie w całym Sejmie zbliżano , a w dniu 3 maja 1791 dokonano ( A Declaration to the Nation with a Protestation for the Evidence of Rape and Violence which was Planned throughout most of the Sejm and on day 3 May 1791 Carried out ) . [ 19 ]
#Text=Suchorzewski on Jan Matejko 's painting Constitution of May 3 , 1791

#Text=Suchorzewski , with several other opponents of the constitution , departed to Saint Petersburg in the Russian Empire , where he became one of the founding members and high-ranking officials ( konsyliarz ) of the Confederation of Targowica . [ 1 ] [ 20 ] [ 21 ]

#Text=Derdej speculated that out of all those who signed the act of the Confederation , Suchorzewski was the only one who might have thought they were really acting in the country 's best interest . [ 17 ]
#Text=He commanded a cavalry brigade in the Confederation forces during the War in Defense of the Constitution that the Confederates eventually won , overthrowing the Constitution .
#Text=During the Kościuszko Insurrection he was sentenced , in absentia , to a death by hanging , eternal infamy , loss of all titles and confiscation of possessions .
#Text=His effigy was hanged on the 29 September 1794 . [ 22 ]
